  "text": "## HTTP Health Check Endpoint Comparison\n\n### Kubernetes/Kubernetes\n\n**Endpoints**: `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`\n\n**Implementation Files**:\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go`: Core health checking framework with `HealthChecker` interface and handler installation functions\n- `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz.go`: GenericAPIServer integration with health check registry management\n\n**Key Components**:\n- **HealthChecker Interface**: Named health checkers that perform individual checks. Built-in checkers include:\n  - `PingHealthz`: Always returns healthy\n  - `LogHealthz`: Checks if logging is not blocked\n  - `InformerSyncHealthz`: Checks if informers are synced (used for readyz)\n  - `ShutdownHealthz`: Fails when shutdown signal is received\n  - Custom named checks via `NamedCheck()` and `NamedGroupedCheck()`\n\n- **Registration Pattern**: `InstallHandler()`, `InstallReadyzHandler()`, and `InstallLivezHandler()` functions register health endpoints on a mux with a list of HealthChecker instances\n\n- **Checks Performed**:\n  - `/healthz`: Backward compatibility endpoint, includes ping and custom checks\n  - `/livez` (liveness): Checks if the process is alive (with configurable grace period via `livezGracePeriod`)\n  - `/readyz` (readiness): Strict checks ensuring the server can handle traffic (informer sync, etcd access, KMS health, etc.)\n\n- **Graceful Shutdown**: `AddBootSequenceHealthChecks()` and `AddReadyzShutdownCheck()` allow configuring shutdown behavior\n\n### Grafana/Grafana\n\n**Endpoints**: `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`, `/api/health`\n\n**Implementation Files**:\n- `pkg/server/health.go`: Core health endpoint handlers (`LivezHandler`, `ReadyzHandler`)\n- `pkg/api/http_server.go`: HTTP server integration and health check middleware registration\n\n**Key Components**:\n- **HealthNotifier**: Thread-safe mechanism to signal readiness state using atomic bool\n  - `SetReady()`: Mark operator as ready\n  - `SetNotReady()`: Mark operator as not ready\n  - `IsReady()`: Check readiness status\n\n- **Handler Implementations**:\n  - `LivezHandler()`: Always returns 200 OK (process is alive)\n  - `ReadyzHandler(HealthNotifier)`: Returns 200 OK if ready, 503 Service Unavailable if not ready\n  - `healthzHandler()`: Simple middleware-based check, returns 200 OK if server is running\n  - `apiHealthHandler()`: Checks database connectivity, returns 200 if database is OK, 503 if failing. Includes version info in response\n\n- **Checks Performed**:\n  - `/healthz`: Basic server running check (always 200)\n  - `/readyz`: Operator readiness state (depends on `HealthNotifier.SetReady()` being called)\n  - `/livez`: Process liveness (always 200)\n  - `/api/health`: Database connectivity check, returns JSON with database status and version information\n\n- **Registration**: Handlers are registered as middleware using `m.Use(handler)` in the HTTP server setup\n\n### Prometheus/Prometheus\n\n**Endpoints**: `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready`\n\n**Implementation Files**:\n- `web/web.go`: Main handler registration and readiness checking logic\n- `cmd/prometheus/main.go`: Server initialization and readiness state management\n\n**Key Components**:\n- **Handler**: Main web handler managing the application's ready state\n  - `SetReady(status ReadyStatus)`: Sets the ready status (Ready, NotReady, or Stopping)\n  - `isReady()`: Checks current ready status\n  - `testReady(f http.HandlerFunc)`: Middleware that wraps handlers to enforce ready status checks\n\n- **ReadyStatus Enum**: Three states:\n  - `Ready`: Server is operational and accepting traffic\n  - `NotReady`: Server is initializing but may become ready\n  - `Stopping`: Server is shutting down gracefully\n\n- **Handler Implementations**:\n  - `/-/healthy`: Always returns 200 OK (\"<AppName> is Healthy.\")\n  - `/-/ready`: Wraps response with `testReady()` middleware\n    - Returns 200 OK when in Ready state\n    - Returns 503 Service Unavailable with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: false` header when NotReady\n    - Returns 503 Service Unavailable with `X-Prometheus-Stopping: true` header when Stopping\n  - Both endpoints support GET and HEAD methods\n\n- **Checks Performed**:\n  - `/-/healthy`: Always succeeds (simple liveness indicator)\n  - `/-/ready`: Checks internal ready state managed by `SetReady()` during server initialization and shutdown. Ready status is set after TSDB initialization completes and unset during graceful shutdown.\n\n### Comparison Summary\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | Grafana | Prometheus |\n|--------|-----------|---------|------------|\n| **Architecture** | Pluggable health checker framework | State-based readiness with database check | State-based with graceful shutdown tracking |\n| **Liveness** | `/livez` with grace period | `/livez` (always 200) | `/-/healthy` (always 200) |\n| **Readiness** | `/readyz` with rich checks | `/readyz` (state-based) | `/-/ready` (state-based) |\n| **Dependencies Checked** | Informers, etcd, KMS, custom | Database connectivity | Internal initialization state |\n| **Shutdown Support** | Explicit shutdown health check | (via HealthNotifier) | Dedicated Stopping state with header |\n| **Response Format** | Text (\"ok\" or error list) | Text/JSON (database status, version) | Text (status message) |\n| **Extensibility** | Add custom HealthChecker instances | Extend via HealthNotifier signals | Modify SetReady() calls in main |\n"
